Why network analysis?¶

  • Law involves relational data, for which networks are promising.

  • In terms of methods we are behind the times (cfr. economics, psychology, political science).

  • Law deals with categorical variables. It is only recently that methods for dealing with categorical variables have become widespread and easy to teach and to use.

  • Network Analysis can provide insight in datasets smaller than those typically required by other methods.

  • The math involved in network analysis is approachable. A lot more can be learned with just sums and averages, in comparison with linear regression (where OLS already requires higher level math). Add matrix multiplication and one is in ok shape.

  • (otoh a relatively high level of python is needed. You need to be comfortable with dictionaries, views and list comprehensions, more so than with Scikit-learn, Pandas or Statsmodels)

  • it is very general, see below:

Jurimetric relations:¶

  • articles related to other articles
  • cases citing other cases
  • document similarity networks

Also socio-legal relations¶

  • Connections between actors
  • Criminal networks
  • Companies sharing a CEO or other high official
  • Degree of separation between private sector and public sector in a country.
  • Connections between interviewees.

Legal Reasoning and Argumentation¶

  • Arguments can be seen as forming a network structure.
  • And so can value rankings.
  • Networks may be used as an evaluation tool.

Very general¶

Networks are in the end just one more data type that can be inserted into any machine learning algorithm (with some work)

  • P. Seidler & R. Adderley (2013). Criminal Network Analysis inside Law Enforcement Agencies: A Data-Mining System Approach under the National Intelligence Model. International Journal of Police Science & Management, 15(4), 323–337

Datasets¶

Here we will only use 3 networks

  • The Krackhard Kite graph, which is purely abstract, but helps us compare different centrality measures.
  • Zachary's karate club graph, which is based on real social research, and will be most useful for trying to show the power of networks to provide predictions in real world scenarios.
  • A small network of citations between ECHR Grand Chamber judgements that consider the topic of extraterritorial obligations. This will be mostly to introduce a directed, legal example. However this network is more complicated than the others.

Terminology¶

Nodes¶

Nodes are the dots of the network, they represent the entities that are related by edges.

Edges¶

Edges join nodes together (or not). Every edge represents ONE type of relationship:

  • "i is friends with j"
  • "i Cites j"
  • "i is to this extent w similar or different to j"

Edges can be directed or undirected. A friendship is normally undirected, citations are directed.

Edges can be unweighted and to that extent network analysis is purely qualitative, or they can be weighted and then it has a quantiative dimension.

Path¶

A path is a traversal from one node to another. Of greatest interest here are shortest paths. IE. what is the shortest path to get from node 2 to node 8?

Centrality Measures¶

These record which nodes of the network are more important (more important cases, more important participants of a criminal network, more important interviews),

Degree Centrality¶

The easiest measure only records the amount of neighbors a node has, ie. its degree and divides it by n-1 to normalize it to the size of the network (having 5 neighbors in a network of 6 nodes is a big deal, having 5 neighbors in a network of 600 nodes, possibly is not).

$$ \frac{degree(n)}{|N|-1} \mid n \in N $$

Looking at the kite, node 3 is the clear winner. We can see that just by looking. It has a degree of 6.

draw_spring(g_kite)

Can we use degree centrality to figure who is the President and Instructor?

Closeness Centrality¶

Closeness centrality expresses the average closeness between a target node $ u $ and the set of all other nodes it can reach $ V $, when taking the shortest path between the node under examination and the reachable nodes (this shortest path is often called the 'geodesic path'). The greater the average closeness of one node to all other nodes using the shortest paths, the more central the node is. Remember here that closeness is the reciprocal of the distance it appears as at inverse average:

$$ \frac{|V|-1}{\sum_{V_1}^{V_n}spath(v,u)} $$

Remember that 3 was the winning node in degree centrality? Closeness changes things, because it takes into account indirect connections. Nodes 5 and 6 have shorter paths to access nodes 7 8 and 9, so they score higher here than node 3.

Betweeness Centrality¶

Now we will consider as most central not just nodes that have a lot of neighbors, but nodes that are "mediators" (or "brokers") in the network. These nodes are the glue that holds the network together. If they are removed, this can cause severe disruption in the network, possibly disconnecting parts of the network.

$$ \sum_{s,t \in V} \frac{spaths(s, t \mid v)}{spath(s, t)} $$

Once more looking at the kite, from a betweeness perspective, node 7 becomes the winner because it is the "broker" between 8 and 9 and the rest of the kite. If we remove node 7, the network falls apart.

Pagerank¶

PageRank is a variant of the Eigenvector centrality which is applicable to directed networks. Like Eigenvector Centrality it considers not only the number of links one receives, but also the popularity of those linking to us. It is also based on the "random walk idea": the Pagerank score corresponds to the likelihood of a user ending up on that page by randomly clicking from link to link.

The math of pagerank is a little bit more complicated, but you can see it in the textbook. The general idea can be explained as repeated updating of a vector that by a matrix representing the network. A sketch below: (but pagerank does not use the adjacency matrix, nor does HITS, see textbook).

HITS¶

HITS Is similar to pagerank in using a random walker model, but provides results of both authorities (imoprtant notes) and hubs (nodes that cite important nodes)

In [18]:

hubs = results_hits[0].values()
authorities = results_hits[1].values()

I find it unsurprising that Georgia v. Russsia is a Hub

Community Detection¶

Louvain Communities¶

Louvain communities is a graph algorithm that identifies clusters in the graph using the network itself. It is based on the modularity score. The math here is somewhat complicated but can be seen in the textbook.

What Louvain does is to iteratively partition the network into subparts by joining nodes together, and keeps doing this while the modularity score remains positive.

Louvain is a random process to some extent, so what you get may vary. Here unmodified it detects 4 communities, the friends of the President, the friends of the Instructor, and two "straggler" communities.

In [22]:
